title: For Trade:  Colt ivory grips (for Colt ivory grips)
postcontent: Okay here's the thing: I found some real elephant ivory grips at a gun show, advertised by the seller as made to fit a Colt Mustang. As you can see from the pictures, they have a vivid, unmistakeable grain that, in addition to being gorgeous, is something that no snythetic ivory substitute has ever or could ever hope to replicate, and it should therefore be obvious to anyone that they are the real deal. They are marked "Hand Crafted for Colt Firearms" on the back in blue ink, and he actually had several other sets of ivory grips marked in the same fashion.  According to the seller, this mark indicates that they were all made by Jim Alaimo, who would later go on to found Nutmeg Sports, during his time as the overseer of the Colt Custom Shop. (I cannot myself attest to this, but some searching with google does seem to indicate this is the truth.) Though they seemed a bit long for a Mustang, he assured me they were made to fit that exact model and that they would require no special fitting to go on one.Having a Colt Mustang, I bought them, only to find that my suspicions were correct, and they were indeed about 3/4 of an inch too long to fit my pistol. To be fair, it appears that the seller was not entirely incorrect, as they would indeed have fit my Mustang if it had been a Colt Mustang "PLUS II" model, which is a variantion that mated the shortened slide of the Colt Mustang with the full size frame of the Colt .380 Government Model (not the full size Colt Government Model, mind you...the .380 Government is a different beast, or approximately a 3/4 scale recreation of one). I will therefore repeat: these grips are made to fit either a Colt Government .380 or Colt Mustang Plus II.This is the mother of all longshots, but I will trade my ivory grips that will beautifully fit either of these two classic Colts for grips of an equally valuable material that will fit a Colt Mustang. Materials I consider of equal value include elephant, walrus, and hippo ivory, fossil ivories such as mammoth and walrus, engraved sterling silver, genuine mother of pearl, and musk ox boss. Sambar stag might possibly approach a near equal value, but only if it is a truly exceptional example of such with the most impressive popcorn texture, and so might select examples of jigged bone, but again only if it is of such an exquisite grade as I doubt has ever been made to fit a gun this modern. I have no interest in trading for any synthetic ivory or pearl substitutes and probably not any woods.

In Lieu Of The Inferior Alloy Grade, The Lifter/Carrier Was Changed To A Stamped, Rather Than A Forged Part. Post 64 Were Stamped... A Less Durable Metal Finish Was Substituted For The Traditional Bluing Pre 64 Bluing Was High Polished In Lieu Of The Post 64 Polishing &The Loading Gate Became A Stamped And Riveted Part, Which Was Also Obvious. And Hollow Steel Roll Pins, Which Just Plain Looked Cheap, Replaced The Solid Steel Action Pins, Pre 64 Had The Controlled Round Feed Feature. The Steel Buttplate Became Plastic, The Mainspring Was Changed To A Coil Spring.
